File: Money. eNCA JOHANNESBURG - South African retailer Pepkor says it expects half-year earnings to increase by at least 20 percent. It says this has been supported by growth at its discount clothing business. The company has also been able to reduce its debt. READ: Steinhoff Africa Retail to revert name back to Pepkor It comes as South African clothing retailers continue to struggle, with consumers having less disposable income. But, Pepkor, which is majority-owned by Steinhoff, has benefited from its focus on budget-conscious consumers. These consumers include over 17 million South Africans on welfare and special COVID-19 grants. The furniture, appliances and electronics division, which includes Incredible Connection and Hi-Fi Corporation has reported revenue growth of over 12-percent thanks to more people working and studying from home.